'''Takakura Family''' (高倉家) refers to a {{ill|Kuge|ja|公家|1=Kuge|12=draft}} lineage of the {{ill|Fujiwara Hokke|ja|藤原北家|12=draft}}, tracing their descent from {{ill|Takakura Nagasue|ja|高倉永季|12=draft}}, a {{ill|Sangi|ja|参議|12=draft}} and holder of {{ill|Junior Second Rank|ja|従二位|1=Junior Second Rank|12=draft}}. As a {{ill|Kuge|ja|公家|1=Kuge|12=draft}}, their status was classified as {{ill|Half-House|ja|半家|12=draft}}, and under the {{ill|Kazoku|ja|華族|12=draft}} system, they were ennobled as {{ill|Viscount|ja|子爵|12=draft}} {{Sfn|Ota Ryo|1934|p=3274}}.

Their branch family, the {{ill|Horikawa Family|ja|堀河家|12=draft}}, also belonged to the {{ill|Feather-Forest House|ja|羽林家|12=draft}} and held the {{ill|Viscount|ja|子爵|12=draft}} title {{sfn|Kazoku Daikan Kanko Kai|1990|p=413}}.

== History ==

The family originated with {{ill|Fujiwara Nagano|ja|藤原長良|12=draft}}, a son of [[:en:Fujiwara no Fuyutsugu|Fujiwara no Fuyutsugu]], and developed through his sixth son {{ill|Fujiwara Kiyotsune|ja|藤原清経|12=draft}} {{Sfn|Kazoku Daikan Kanko Kai|1990|p=164}}. Over the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft}}, few family members achieved {{ill|Kugyō|ja|Kugyō|1=Kugyō|12=draft}} rank<ref name="kotobank">{{Cite Kotobank|word=高倉家|encyclopedia=世界大百科事典 第２版、日本大百科全書(ニッポニカ)|accessdate=2022-11-16}}</ref>. In the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代|12=draft}}, {{ill|Takakura Nagasue|ja|高倉永季|12=draft}} elevated the family name by attaining the rank of {{ill|Sangi|ja|参議|12=draft}}, establishing the Takakura family line.

The family name "Takakura" derives from their residence in the Takakura district of Kyoto<ref name="kotobank"/>. Their household responsibilities included overseeing court garments and the hereditary {{ill|Emondō|ja|衣紋道|12=draft}} tradition <ref name="kotobank"/>.

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft}}, the Takakura family possessed a stipend of 812 koku, with lands in {{ill|Yamashiro Province|ja|Yamashiro Province|12=draft}}. Their main residence was located in Nikaimachi, and their {{ill|Bodaiji|ja|菩提寺|12=draft}} was the Jōgen-in temple at Kurodani {{SFn|Ota Ryo|1934|p=3274}}.

=== Bakumatsu Period and Meiji Restoration ===

In the {{ill|Bakumatsu|ja|幕末|12=draft}} period, the head of the family, {{ill|Takakura Nagayoshi|ja|高倉永祜|12=draft}}, played a significant role in the {{ill|Boshin War|ja|戊辰戦争|12=draft}}, serving as a general in various campaigns. However, he died in 1868 in Echigo Province during the war<ref>{{Cite Kotobank|word=高倉永祜|encyclopedia=デジタル版 日本人名大辞典+Plus|accessdate=2022-11-16}}</ref>.

In 1869, under the new {{ill|Kazoku|ja|華族|12=draft}} system, the Takakura family was ennobled as part of the {{ill|Kazoku|ja|華族|12=draft}} hierarchy. In 1884, {{ill|Takakura Naganori|ja|高倉永則|12=draft}}, a former military officer, was granted the title of {{ill|Viscount|ja|子爵|12=draft}} {{sfn|Odabe Yuji|2006|p=332}}.

== Notable Members ==
- {{ill|Takakura Nagasue|ja|高倉永季|12=draft}}
- {{ill|Takakura Nagayoshi|ja|高倉永祜|12=draft}}
- {{ill|Takakura Naganori|ja|高倉永則|12=draft}}

== Related Institutions ==

The family archives, including historical documents, texts, and ceremonial garments, are preserved by the Yūsoku Cultural Institute (formerly the Takakura Cultural Institute). This organization is committed to preserving the traditions associated with the Takakura lineage.

